reviews.review_text:
Excellent matrix 1986 was a pretty bleak year for the Grateful Dead.  Jerry had his (first) coma in July, and before that the shows weren't all that great.  The guy at deadlistening.com wrote, "There are few things more frightening to most Grateful Dead tape collectors than shows from 1986."

After a five month break the band returned to the stage in December for 3 nights at the Oakland Coliseum, then started their New Year's run ten days later with this show.  There are 16 other copies available on IA, and as of this writing only 526 views of this version.  It is, however, the only matrix of this show.

And it is really well done.  You hear the crowd roar as the band takes the stage, then the music takes over.  If I had already downloaded either a SB or an AU I'd replace it with this version.  Kevin Tobin did a really nice job with this, and the show deserves more views.

This was a fun setlist with the entire show becoming a Playing in the Band sandwich.  I don't know if that was ever done before (or after) but makes for a pretty cool show.  Neither as the opener nor the 2nd set closer is Playing especially long or spacey, but it is a great vehicle, sort of like the Sugar Mag/SSDD sandwich that was the first set of 12/31/78.

The early songs of the first set are played at a frenetic pace.  My first thought was 'Jerry's coked to the gills.'  In comments to other versions of this show people rave about Birdsong, but for me the Rooster (a different bird song, sorry, couldn't resist) was the highlight of the  short, 50 minute first set.

The Mighty Quinn to open the 2nd set sends the crowd into a frenzy, which is wonderful to hear on a matrix.  Truckin' is a bit abbreviated, with a quick transition to Smokestack Lightning after the climax.  Comes A Time is pin drop quiet and also gets raved about on other versions.  On paper the Push Comes to Shove encore seems so wrong, but this is an excellent version and I rather enjoyed it, surprisingly.

I came here because I had no 1986 show in my collection (well, duh, it was 1986) and thought I ought to have at least one.  I chose this particular show for the setlist, and chose this version for the matrix.  Did I mention it is the ONLY matrix available of this show, added to IA in November 2018?  

It is still 1986, however, so don't get your hopes too high.  But this matrix is exceptional in sound quality.  Kudos to Kevin.
